<ns5218:section xmlns:ns5218="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.lang.basicLanguage.operators.assignment">
    <ns5219:title xmlns:ns5219="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Assignment</ns5219:title>
    <ns5220:para xmlns:ns5220="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">You can assign one variable of a basic data type to a constant or to the value of another
        variable. For example</ns5220:para>
    <ns5221:para xmlns:ns5221="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        <ns5222:programlisting xmlns:ns5222="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
double x = 7, y;

 y = x;
    </ns5222:programlisting>
    </ns5221:para>
    <ns5223:para xmlns:ns5223="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">assigns <ns5224:literal xmlns:ns5224="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">x</ns5224:literal> to the constant 7 and then <ns5225:literal xmlns:ns5225="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">y</ns5225:literal> to the value
        of <ns5226:literal xmlns:ns5226="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">x</ns5226:literal>. Hence, the value of y is 7 after the last statement.</ns5223:para>
    <ns5227:para xmlns:ns5227="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">The assignment operator is also defined for object references, but not for the objects
        themselves. We shall come back to this issue later in the book.</ns5227:para>
    <ns5228:para xmlns:ns5228="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"/>
</ns5218:section>